<subSubSection id="7CB0CFACFF85FFC96E11FDF0FB9E574A" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="34159C27FF85FFC96E11FDF0FC5751CA" blockId="23.[113,1089,530,1129]" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis id="06DE4035FF85FFC96E11FDF0FF3F510A" bold="true" box="[113,224,530,553]" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="503BE1D6FF85FFC96E85FDF0FE46510A" author="UHMANN E." box="[229,409,530,553]" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" pagination="209 - 256" refId="ref20564" refString="UHMANN E. 1930 b: Hispinen aus Costa Rica aus der Ausbeute des Herrn Ferd. Nevermann. 20. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Hispinen (Col. Chrys.). Folia Zoologica et Hydrobiologica 1: 209 - 256." type="journal article" year="1930">UHMANN (1930b)</bibRefCitation>
described this species based on a single specimen and stated that it was collected on flowers. The 
<typeStatus id="EB112285FF85FFC96FB0FDD0FDF2516A" box="[464,557,562,585]" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">holotype</typeStatus>
is strongly damaged missing both antennae from the antennomere II on and right elytron is broken due to the pin. In my opinion this species does not belong to 
<taxonomicName id="F3AAE7A4FF85FFC96F5DFD90FE6051AA" authorityName="Chevrolat in Dejean" authorityYear="1836" box="[317,447,626,649]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="06DE4035FF85FFC96F5DFD90FE6051AA" box="[317,447,626,649]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">Cephaloleia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as it has conspicuously serrate apical margin of elytra, long antennae compared to the length of body and smooth convex frons and vertex. These characters are typical for the genus 
<taxonomicName id="F3AAE7A4FF85FFC96FA7FD50FDC251EA" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1859" box="[455,541,690,713]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Xenispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="06DE4035FF85FFC96FA7FD50FDC251EA" box="[455,541,690,713]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">Xenispa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F3AAE7A4FF85FFC96C30FD50FD1D51EA" authorityName="Uhmann" authorityYear="1930" box="[592,706,690,713]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephalolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilvipes">
<emphasis id="06DE4035FF85FFC96C30FD50FD1D51EA" box="[592,706,690,713]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">C. gilvipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
conforms to other species currently classified in that genus. Therefore I hereby transfer 
<taxonomicName id="F3AAE7A4FF85FFC96CF7FD30FCD651CA" authorityName="Uhmann" authorityYear="1930" box="[663,777,722,745]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephalolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilvipes">
<emphasis id="06DE4035FF85FFC96CF7FD30FCD651CA" box="[663,777,722,745]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">C. gilvipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="F3AAE7A4FF85FFC96D4BFD30FC5E51CA" authorityName="Baly" authorityYear="1859" box="[811,897,722,745]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Xenispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="06DE4035FF85FFC96D4BFD30FC5E51CA" box="[811,897,722,745]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">Xenispa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="34159C27FF85FFC96EF0FD10FC59570A" blockId="23.[113,1089,530,1129]" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">
The species was so far reported only three times based on specimens collected in high mountains of central 
<collectingCountry id="4CBDDCB7FF85FFC96F36FCF0FE13500A" box="[342,460,786,809]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
above 
<quantity id="F35231C2FF85FFC96C7BFCF0FDB2500A" box="[539,621,786,809]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" unit="m" value="1500.0">1500 m</quantity>
a.s.l. (
<bibRefCitation id="503BE1D6FF85FFC96CD5FCF0FC15500A" author="FLOWERS R. W. &amp; HANSON P. E." box="[693,970,786,809]" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" pagination="25 - 51" refId="ref19968" refString="FLOWERS R. W. &amp; HANSON P. E. 2003: The diversity of the Chrysomelidae fauna in Costa Rica: Insights from a Malaise trapline. Pp. 25 - 51. In: FURTH D. G. (ed.): Special Topics in Leaf Beetle Biology. Pensoft, Series Faunistica 29, Sofia-Moscow, xii + 339 pp." type="book chapter" year="2003">FLOWERS &amp; HANSON 2003</bibRefCitation>
, MCKENNA &amp; FARELL 2005, STAINES &amp; GARCÍA- ROBLEDO 2014). I had no opportunity to verify any of the recently published specimens, thus I cannot confirm their identifications. The specimens reported here agree perfectly with the 
<typeStatus id="EB112285FF85FFC96C62FC90FDBD50AA" box="[514,610,882,905]" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">holotype</typeStatus>
, having the same shape, colouration and punctation. Particularly characteristic is the shape of pronotum as it has only very narrow lateral margins, which are not explanate. A similarly shaped pronotum is known only in 
<taxonomicName id="F3AAE7A4FF85FFC96D8BFC50FE9850CA" authority="(Pic, 1934)" baseAuthorityName="Pic" baseAuthorityYear="1934" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Xenispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="uhmanni">
<emphasis id="06DE4035FF85FFC96D8BFC50FF1150CA" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">Xenispa uhmanni</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="503BE1D6FF85FFC96EBBFC30FEE050CA" author="PIC M." box="[219,319,978,1001]" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref20264" refString="PIC M. 1934: Nouveautes diverses, notes. Melanges Exotico-Entomologiques 63: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="1934">Pic, 1934</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="4CBDDCB7FF85FFC96FE4FC30FE3050CA" box="[388,495,978,1001]" name="Colombia" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, which differs in having black antennae and legs while 
<taxonomicName id="F3AAE7A4FF85FFC96A4AFC30FF1B572A" authorityName="Uhmann" authorityYear="1930" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephalolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilvipes">
<emphasis id="06DE4035FF85FFC96A4AFC30FF1B572A" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">X. gilvipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has them pale brown. The locality Cañon is situated on the Pan-American Highway and is about 
<quantity id="F35231C2FF85FFC96E99FBF0FEF0570A" box="[249,303,1042,1065]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" unit="km" value="6.0">6 km</quantity>
air distance to NW from the type locality of 
<taxonomicName id="F3AAE7A4FF85FFC96D6EFBF0FCA0570A" authorityName="Uhmann" authorityYear="1930" box="[782,895,1042,1065]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephalolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilvipes">
<emphasis id="06DE4035FF85FFC96D6EFBF0FCA0570A" box="[782,895,1042,1065]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="374">X. gilvipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
